===Etymology 1===
[[Image:Kovas.jpg|thumb|A rook (bird)]]

* From {{inh|en|enm|rok}}, {{m|enm|roke}}, from {{inh|en|ang|hrōc}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*hrōk}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*hrōkaz}} (compare {{cog|non|hrókr}}, {{cog|stq|Rouk}}, {{cog|nl|roek}}, obsolete {{cog|de|Ruch}}), from {{der|en|ine-pro|*kerk-|t=crow, raven}} (compare {{cog|sga|cerc||hen}}, {{cog|prg|kerko||loon, diver}}, dialectal {{cog|bg|кро́кон||raven}}, {{cog|grc|κόραξ||crow}}, {{cog|xcl|ագռաւ}}, {{cog|ae|𐬐𐬀𐬵𐬭𐬐𐬀𐬙𐬀𐬝|t=rooster}}, {{cog|sa|कृकर|t=rooster}}), {{cog|uk|крук||raven}}.
* {{sense|parson}} Probably from the resemblance in plumage to a parson's garments.

====Noun====
{{en-noun|~}}

# A European [[bird]], ''[[Corvus frugilegus]]'', of the [[crow]] family.
#* '''1768''', Thomas Pennant, ''British Zoology'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=oG9bAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA169 168]:
#*: But what distinguishes the '''rook''' from the crow is the bill; the nostrils, chin, and sides of that and the mouth being in old birds white and bared of feathers, by often thrusting the bill into the ground in search of the erucæ of the Dor-beetle*; the rook then, instead of being proscribed, should be treated as the farmer's friend; as it clears his ground from caterpillars, that do incredible damage by eating the roots of the corn.
# A [[cheat]] or [[swindler]]; someone who [[betray]]s.
#: {{syn|en|Thesaurus:deceiver|Thesaurus:fraudster}}
#* 7 April '''1705''', William Wycherley, Letter to Alexander Pope in ''The Works of Alexander Pope'' [https://books.google.com/books?id=shcrAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA36 36]:
#*: So I am (like an old '''rook''', who is ruined by gaming) forced to live on the good fortune of the pushing young men, whose fancies are so vigorous that they ensure their success in their adventures with Muses, by their strength and imagination.
# A bad deal; a [[rip-off]].
# {{lb|en|British}} A type of [[firecracker]] used by farmers to scare birds of the same name.
# {{lb|en|uncountable}} A trick-taking game, usually played with a specialized deck of cards.
#* '''2007''', Malcolm Bull and Keith Lockhart, ''Seeking a Sanctuary: Seventh-day Adventism and the American Dream'', [https://books.google.com/books?id=ACUBSUGQCMYC&pg=PA174 174]:
#*: Adventists still do not really know how to play cards, apart from the sanitized version of bridge, '''Rook'''.
# {{lb|en|slang|archaic}} A [[parson]].

